                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote scope="major" script="ta_liq" medium="ink"> Written in elegant
                           <material>black</material> ta‘līq by <persName key="person_f8488"
                           xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc">Darvīsh ‘Alī bin Pīr Aḥmad al-Mashhadī
                           al-Mubashir</persName>. </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <additions>
                     <lb/>
                     <label>Marginalia:</label> Notes in various hands written between the lines and
                     in the margins. <lb/>
                     <label>Inscriptions:</label>
                     <list type="bulleted">
                        <item>The <locus from="ia" to="ia">right flyleaf a side (f. ia)</locus>
                           bears the title in nasta‘līq script, probably in the hand of <persName
                              role="wst" key="person_f6587">Muhīn Dās</persName>, assistant to
                           former owner <persName type="supplied" key="person_f830" role="fmo"
                              change="#role-assignment">Colonel George William Hamilton</persName>. </item>
                        <item>Folio <locus from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus> bears several notations:
                              <list type="bulleted">
                              <item>
                                 <label>Top:</label> Three inscriptions in various hands on the
                                 upper-left corner all record the title in Persian, one partly
                                 legible, but two noting a price of 15 in Indic sīyāq script. A
                                 comparatively bold script bears a number <q>279</q> underneath. </item>
                              <item>
                                 <label>Middle:</label> An inspection notation by probable Awadh
                                 royal library attendant <persName role="ins ato asn"
                                    key="person_f7824">Muḥammad Bayg</persName> dated <date
                                    calendar="#Hijri-qamari" from="1815" to="1816">1231 AH (1815–16
                                    CE)</date>, who similary signed other volumes now held in the Rylands:<lb/>
                                 <q> اهتمام محمد بیگ سنه ۱۲۳۱</q><lb/>
                                 <q>Ihtimām Muḥammad Bayg sanah 1231 (Inspected by Muḥammad Bayg,
                                    year 1231)</q>.</item>
                           </list>
                        </item>
                     </list>
                     <label>Bookplates:</label> The <locus from="Inner_back_cover"
                        to="Inner_back_cover">left doublure</locus>: <q xml:lang="en">Bibliotheca
                        Lindesiana</q> with pencilled shelfmark <q xml:lang="en">1/F</q>, and <q
                        xml:lang="en"><hi rend="strikethrough">Hamilton</hi> MSS No. <hi
                           rend="strikethrough">445</hi></q>, with the name and number crossed out
                     and <q xml:lang="en">Persian</q> and <q xml:lang="en">528</q> written aside. </additions>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding calendar="#Gregorian" notBefore="1737" notAfter="1835">
                        <p>Probably rebound in a hydrid British-Indian style in <placeName
                              ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7002481" key="place_7002481"
                              >Multan</placeName> for former owner <persName type="supplied"
                              key="person_f830" role="fmo" change="#role-assignment">George William
                              Hamilton</persName> between <date cert="high" calendar="#Gregorian"
                              from="1858" to="1862">1858 and 1862</date>.</p>
                        <p>Resewn at two stations, unsupported. Edges trimmed, the <locus
                              from="Head" to="Head">head</locus> coloured black, and chevron
                           endbands of green and red silk threads twined at <locus from="Head"
                              to="Head">head</locus> and <locus from="Tail" to="Tail">tail</locus>.
                           Covered in full maroon-coloured goatskin <material>leather</material>
                           over <material>pasteboards</material>, without a flap but with squares at
                           the edges and defined joints (type III binding per Déroche). Internal
                           doublures lined with the same leather, their excess widths adhered as
                           hinges to the flyleaves to connect the cover to the text, with strips of
                           paper, decoratively cut with zig-zags along one edges, applied over top
                           to disguise the joins.</p>

                        <decoNote type="binding">Board margins painted black with foliate palmette
                           vines, similar to Rylands <ref
                              target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_7029"
                                 ><idno>Persian MS 533</idno></ref>, <ref
                              target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_7030">534</ref>,
                           and <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_7035"
                              >539</ref>. Title handwritten in nasta‘līq script on the <locus
                              from="Spine" to="Spine">spine</locus> within a hand-painted gold
                           cartouche.</decoNote>
                        <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                              <height>228</height>
                              <width>141</width>
                              <depth>22</depth>
                           </dimensions></p>
                        <condition>Binding in fair but stable condition.</condition>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
                  <sealDesc>
                     <summary>Two vermilion library seal impressions on folio <locus from="1a"
                           to="1a">1a</locus>, both intaglio-carved in nasta‘līq script in two
                        stacked lines, of the kings of <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001502" key="place_7001502">Awadh
                           (Oude)</placeName>, along with a small rectangular intaglio-carved
                           <material>black</material> impression on folio <locus from="99b" to="99b"
                           >99b</locus>.</summary>

                     <seal type="stamp" subtype="rectangle">
                        <p><label>1:</label> Folios <locus from="1b" to="1b">1b</locus> and <locus
                              from="115b" to="115b">115b</locus> bear rectangular library seal
                           impressions of <persName role="fmo seal"
                              ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/265857376" key="person_265857376">Nāṣir
                              al-Dīn Ḥaydar Shāh (b. 1803, r. 1827–1837)</persName>, within two
                           stacked cartouches, double-ruled and dated <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari"
                              notBefore="1828" notAfter="1829">1244 AH (1828–1829 CE)</date>,
                           inscribed with his title <addName type="epithet"
                              ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/265857376" key="person_265857376">Sulaymān
                              Jāh</addName>::<lb/><q xml:lang="fa"> خوش است مهر کتبخانه سلیمان جاه *
                              بهر کتاب مزین چو نقش بسم الله، ١٢۴۴</q><lb/>
                           <q xml:lang="en"><hi rend="italic">Khvush ast muhur-i kitābkhānah-'i
                                 Sulaymān Jāh bahr-i kitāb; muzayyin chaw naqsh-i basmallah</hi>,
                                 <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari" notBefore="1828-07-14"
                                 notAfter="1829-07-02">1244 </date></q> (<q xml:lang="en">The seal
                              of the library of Sulaymān Jāh is good; it embellishes the book like
                              the design of a <hi rend="italic">basmallah</hi>, <date
                                 calendar="#Hijri-qamari" notBefore="1828-07-14"
                                 notAfter="1829-07-02">1244 AH</date></q>).<lb/>
                           <dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                              <height>17</height>
                              <width>37</width>
                           </dimensions></p>
                     </seal>
                     <seal type="stamp" subtype="rectangle">
                        <p><label>2:</label> Folios <locus from="1b" to="1b">1b</locus> and <locus
                              from="116b" to="116b">116b</locus> bear rectangular library seal,
                           surmounted by the royal emblem of Awadh, of <persName role=" seal fmo"
                              key="person_9680150325559110090006"
                              ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/9680150325559110090006/">Amjad ‘Alī Shāh
                              (b. 1801, r. 1842–1847)</persName>, beaded-ruled and dated <date
                              calendar="#Hijri-qamari" notBefore="1844-01-22" notAfter="1845-01-09"
                              >1260 AH (1844–1845 CE)</date>, on folios :<lb/>
                           <q xml:lang="fa">ناسخ هر مهر شد چون شد مزین بر کتاب * خاتم امجد علی شاه
                              زمان عالیجناب، ١٢٦٠</q><lb/>
                           <q xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc"><hi rend="italic">Nāsukh har muhur shud chun
                                 shud muzayyin bar kitāb; khātim-i Amjad ‘Alī Shāh zamān-i
                                 ‘Ālījanāb</hi>, <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari"
                                 notBefore="1844-01-22" notAfter="1845-01-09">1260</date></q> (<q
                              xml:lang="en">Every [prior] seal became cancelled since the book
                              became embellished by the seal of Amjad ‘Alī Shāh in the era of his
                              Sublime Majesty, <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari" notBefore="1844-01-22"
                                 notAfter="1845-01-09">1260 AH</date></q>).<lb/>
                           <dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                              <height>53</height>
                              <width>45</width>
                           </dimensions></p>
                     </seal>
                     <seal type="stamp" subtype="rectangle">
                        <p><label>3:</label> Folio Folios <locus from="99b" to="99b">99b</locus>
                           bears two impressions from a small black, rectangular seal in three
                           diagonally stacked nasta‘liq lines, single-rules, with the name of
                              <persName role="seal fmo asn" key="person_f8489">Jagat
                              Narāyin</persName>, probably dated <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari"
                              notBefore="1792" notAfter="1793">1207 AH (1792–1793 CE)</date>:<lb/>
                           <q xml:lang="fa">جگت نراین ١٢۷٠</q><lb/>
                           <lb/>
                           <dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                              <height>9</height>
                              <width>11</width>
                           </dimensions></p>
                     </seal>
                  </sealDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin>Completed by <persName>Darvīsh ‘Alī bin Pīr Aḥmad al-Mashhadī
                        al-Mubashir</persName>, possibly in the <origPlace cert="medium"
                        type="empire" ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/6005089"
                        key="place_6005089">Safavid Empire</origPlace>
                     <origDate calendar="#Hijri-qamari" from="1544" to="1545">951 AH (1544–1545
                        CE)</origDate>.</origin>

                  <provenance><p>Seemingly inspected by <persName role="seal fmo asn"
                           key="person_f8489">Jagat Narāyin</persName>> as per his seal impression
                        on folio <locus>99b</locus>. He may be the same as a poet by that name who
                        completed a panegyric poem honouring the Nawwāb of Awadh <persName
                           role="asn" key="person_4638161696247516120008">Aṣaf al-Dawlah (b. 1748,
                           r. 1795–1797)</persName> upon his death. If correct, it suggests that
                        this manuscript resided in the <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001502">Awadh (Oude)</placeName>
                        royal library in <placeName cert="high"
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/1075256" key="place_1075256"
                           >Faizabad</placeName> at that time.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Transferred to the royal library of <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001502">Awadh (Oude)</placeName> in
                           <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001561"
                           key="place_7001561">Lucknow</placeName>, as indicated by dated library
                        notations on folio <locus from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus>, and seal impressions
                        of the Kings of Awadh <persName type="person" role="fmo seal"
                           key="person_265857376" ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/265857376"> Nāṣir
                           al-Dīn Ḥaydar Shāh (b. 1803, r. 1827–1837)</persName> and <persName
                           role="fmo" key="person_9680150325559110090006"
                           ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/9680150325559110090006"> Amjad ‘Alī Shāh (b.
                           1801, r. 1842–1847)</persName>, then presumably looted during India's
                        First War of Independence, when British soldiers ransacked the Qaisarbagh
                        palace and library on <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1858-03-15">15 March
                           1858</date> (see Wolseley's memoir).</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Subsequently acquired by <persName type="supplied"
                           key="person_f830" role="fmo" change="#role-assignment">Colonel George
                           William Hamilton (1807-1868)</persName> who served in <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208" key="place_7000208"
                           >India</placeName>
                        <date from="1823" to="1867"> from 1823 to 1867</date>, latterly as
                        Commissioner in <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001535"
                           >Delhi</placeName>. He acquired over a thousand Indian and Persian
                        manuscripts, from which the <orgName ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/134857252"
                           >British Museum</orgName> purchased 352 from his widow, <persName
                           key="person_f8470" role="fmo">Charlotte Logie Hamilton
                           (1817–1893)</persName>, now held in the <orgName
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/121814978">British Library</orgName>.</p>
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance><p>
                        <persName role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/"
                           key="person_97751058"> Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford
                           (1812–1880)</persName> purchased the remainder of Hamilton's collection
                     in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1868">1868</date> for his <orgName ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/295427552"
                           key="person_295427552">Bibliotheca Lindesiana</orgName> at Haigh Hall,
                     <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010384"
                        key="place_7010384">Wigan</placeName>.</p>
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Purchased by <persName role="dnr" key="person_f6379"
                           change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" when="1901">1901</date> from <persName role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/" key="person_9985420">James Ludovic
                           Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847–1913)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Bequeathed by <persName key="person_f6379" change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta
                           Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1908"
                           >1908</date> to the <orgName type="corporation" role="rps"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John Rylands Library</orgName>,
                           <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010477"
                           key="place_7010477">Manchester</placeName>.</p>
                  </acquisition>
